<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="A4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>A4: L'Hopital's Rule</title>
    <objectives>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>A4</title>
                <p>
                    I can identify and classify indeterminate forms, and compute them using L’Hopital’s Rule or another applicable technique. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </objectives>

    <xi:include href="./preparation/A4-prep.ptx" />

    <subsection xml:id="A4-activities">
        <title>In-Class Activities</title>

        <activity xml:id="a-activity-lhopital-background1">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In <xref ref="L2"/>, we learned <xref ref="direct-substitution"/>. It says that if <m>f</m> is a <q>nice</q> function (polynomial, algebraic, transcendental, trigonometric), and <m>a</m> is in the domain of <m>f</m>, then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Below, consider the function <m>f(x) = \dfrac{x^2-4}{x-2}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Which option gives the <em>best</em> reason why we can't use Direct Substitution?
                        <ol marker="A.">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The function is not <q>nice</q>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Direct substitution yields a 0 in the denominator
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Direct substutition yields a 0 in the numerator
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Direct substitution yields a 0 in the numerator and the denominator
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Rewrite the function so that you can use Direct Substitution, and then find the limit. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </activity>
    </subsection>

</section>